With an area exceeding 1.1 million hectares, PSEPA is one of the largest marine protected areas in Africa.
Established in 2012, PSEPA is endowed with diversity of habitats, such as mangrove forests, seagrass beds, and coral reefs that support high biodiversity and community livelihood.
However, the region is extremely vulnerable to changes occurring due to increased frequency and intensity of extreme events such as floods, droughts, sea level rise and cyclones.  For instance, in 2019, cyclones Idai and Kenneth caused massive damages to infrastructure thus impacting on community livelihood and wellbeing.
Direct cash payments
My mission to Mozambique was, therefore, to promote an incentive-based scheme that would allow communities to receive direct cash payments through sale of mangrove ecosystem services, in this case carbon credits.
Our pioneering Mikoko Pamoja in Kenya is already saving the endangered mangroves and generating millions of shillings for local communities. Every year, since 2013, communities in Gazi bay of Kwale County receive Sh1.5 million (USD15,000) from the sale of mangrove carbon credits. Income generated from sale of carbon credits is then used to support local development projects in water and sanitation, education, health, and environmental conservation.



