It took almost an hour for the immigration department in Nampula to clear me for Covid-19 and the Yellow Fever. I was booked for an overnight stay at New Hotel Nampula, a splendid facility in the heart of the city. The following morning I was picked for the coastal city of Angoche.
Entry port
According to Wikipedia, Angoche is one of the earliest settlements in Mozambique founded in 1490s by refugees from Kilwa, Tanzania. The city was conquered by the Portuguese in 1860s and continued serving as an important entry port to the interior of the country. Today, Angoche is a quiet and somehow a dilapidated town with few reminders of its glorious past. Processing factories for cashews and coconuts have shut down, forcing communities to seek livelihood opportunities elsewhere, particularly from mangrove and fishery resources.





The distance from Nampula to Angoche is about 180km, but it takes a 3 to 4 hours’ drive due to poor conditions of the road.
Mozambique is a big country, with a coastline exceeding 2,700km; this is more than five times the Kenyan coastline. Infrastructure developments in the northern part of the country have remained low.  This is despite the fact that Ilha de Mozambique, an Island city in Nampula Province, was once the capital city of the country.



