I enquired why the area has generally been marginalised as compared to other parts of the country.  The answer given was that northern Mozambique, including Nampula Province, have remained in opposition politics since independence.
Outside politics, Nampula is a beautiful area. Picturesque protruding bare rocks, expansive Miombo woodlands and large bays and reefs that support white beaches characterise the landscape.
Miombo woodlands are the remnants of extensive coastal forests of Eastern Africa which once stretched from Inhambane in southern Mozambique to Somali. Today, these habitats are fragmented across the coastal areas in the region. In Kenya, coastal forests are represented by the Kayas, Shimba hills, Arabuko-Sokoke and Ngoni forests.
Saving mangroves in PSEPA
Mangrove forests are a characteristic feature of coastal areas of Mozambique in bays, lagoons and estuarine of major rivers.  There are 71,000ha of mangroves in PSEPA representing about 25 per cent of mangroves in the country.  These forests serve as habitats for fish and other wildlife, protect the shoreline from erosion as well as providing harvestable wood and non-wood products to thousands of communities in the area.
PSEPA is within the dune coast of Mozambique and as such, it is characterised by shifting shorelines. Temperature in the area averages 25 degrees centigrade throughout the year. A combination of shifting dunes and scorching temperatures is one of the reasons of low mangrove forest structure in PSEPA. In most of the sites visited, tree height averaged 8 metres with standing biomass of less than 180tonnes/ha, which is much lower than biomass values in Kenya.



