Like in most areas in eastern Africa, mangroves along the coast of Mozambique have been degraded, abused and removed.  In PSEPA, for instance, over-harvesting of wood products, conversion of mangrove areas to other land uses, pollution and climate change effects have severely impacted on the mangroves. Losses and degradation of mangroves has affected local and national economy as witnessed by shortages of firewood and building poles, reduction in fisheries and increased shoreline erosion.
Basic amenities lacking
During reconnaissance surveys that lasted for 10 days, we visited mangroves close to human habitations in Angoche and Moma districts. By any standards, a number of human settlements in PSEPA can be described as poor. The villages lack basic amenities such as schools, clean drinking water, and health facilities. Illiteracy levels are also high, with men in Moma and Angoche districts being ranked as the most illiterate in the Mozambique.
The United Nations categorises Mozambique as a least developed country (LDC).
In 2019, the gross domestic product (GDP) per capita was estimated at USD455. Agriculture, forestry and fisheries sectors are the economic drivers of Mozambique that contribute more than 30 per cent of the GDP.



