Total capture fishery in Mozambique is about 329,000 per year with marine contributing some 70 per cent of this. Some 65,000 people are engaged in fishing activity, both men and women.
Fish consumption
Per capita consumption of fish in Mozambique is 11.6kg compared to the global average rate nearing 20kg. Per capita fish consumption in Kenya is only 4.5kg. 
To sustain the high fish appetite in Mozambique (as everywhere in the world), deliberate efforts must be made to safeguard critical fish habitats that include mangrove swamps.
Overall support from the government for mangrove management in Mozambique is high. The national mangrove management strategy (2017-2027) aims to improve productivity and resilience of mangrove forests for biodiversity conservation and community benefits. It also intends to minimise the effects of global warming through mangrove capture and storage, thus contributing to global development goals and the Paris Agreement. The government has further committed itself to the restoration of 5000ha of degraded mangroves areas. These activities would generate eligible carbon credits that could be traded in the voluntary carbon markets.



