Potential carbon revenue from PSEPA mangroves



if (shouldRenderAd(true)) {
googletag.cmd.push(function () {
googletag.display("mobile-article-ad-8");
});
}



Over the 1998-2018 period, mangroves of PSEPA decreased by 11,200 hectares, translating to an annual loss of 563ha. Such loss activates carbon dioxide emissions from mangrove forests and the sediment. Potential carbon loss from mangroves in PSEPA is estimated at 100 tons of carbon dioxide per hectare, giving total emissions of 56,300 tons of carbon dioxide per year. Payments for ecosystem services schemes such as the UN’s reduced emissions from avoided deforestation and forest degradation (or REDD+) is a potential avenue for rewarding those involved in mangrove conservation activities. Assuming an offset price of USD10 per ton of carbon dioxide, the estimated carbon revenue of mangroves in PSEPA is USD 563,000 per year, plus other co-benefits such as fishery functions and shoreline protection. This justifies our pursuit for a carbon offset project in PSEPA.
The next phase of the project should be defining boundaries where carbon projects can be established within PSEPA. This will be followed by detailed remotes sensing and field surveys to ascertain degradation hotspots and carbon baselines.
Equally important is the commitments from communities targeted for carbon offset projects in PSEPA.  This is achievable through community consultation and capacitation on monitoring, reporting and verification (MRV) of mangrove forest carbon.



