Mozambique is already at an advanced stage of the MRV process in terrestrial forests that is coordinated through the Ministry of Land, Environment and Rural Development. Further, Mozambique has signed the first Emission Reduction Payment Agreements (ERPA) with World Bank, unlocking USD50 million to support the country’s ongoing efforts to reduce carbon emissions from its forest sector.
Being carbon rich ecosystems, mangroves could serve as long hanging fruits for accelerating low carbon pathways in Mozambique at the same time providing livelihood support in the post-Covid recovery period.

Dr Kairo is a Pew Fellow (2019) and Chief Scientist at the Kenya Marine and Fisheries Research Institute.  jkairo@kmfri.co.ke.



